[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Although the number of transistors increased exponentially according to Moore's law, the number of engineers and time taken to produce the designs only increased linearly.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] As the transistors' complexity increases, the number of coding errors also increases.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Most of the errors in logic coding come from careless coding (12.7%), miscommunication (11.4%), and microarchitecture challenges (9.3%).
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Thus, electronic design automation (EDA) tools are produced to catch up with the complexity of transistors design.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Languages such as Verilog and VHDL are introduced together with EDA tools.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Functional verification is very difficult because of the sheer volume of possible test-cases that exist in even a simple design.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Frequently there are more than 1080 possible tests to comprehensively verify a design – a number that is impossible to achieve in a lifetime.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] This effort is equivalent to program verification, and is NP-hard or even worse – and no solution has been found that works well in all cases.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] A functional-verification project is guided by a verification plan.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] This is a foundational document that serves as a blueprint for the entire effort.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] It is a living document created early in the design cycle and is critical for defining scope and tracking progress.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] To measure the completeness of the verification effort, engineers rely on coverage metrics.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Functional verification is not a single, monolithic task but a continuous process that is applied at different levels of design abstraction as a chip is developed.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] This hierarchical approach is necessary to manage the immense complexity of modern SoCs.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Because exhaustive testing is impossible, a combination of methods is used to attack the verification problem.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] These are broadly categorized as dynamic, static, and hybrid approaches.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Dynamic verification involves executing the design model with a given set of input stimuli and checking its output for correct behavior.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] A modern simulation testbench is a complex software environment.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Key components include a generator to create stimuli (often using constrained-random techniques), a driver to translate stimuli into pin-level signals, a monitor to observe outputs, and a checker (or scoreboard) to validate the results against a reference model.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] These approaches combine multiple verification techniques to achieve better results.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] For example, formal methods can be used to generate specific tests that target hard-to-reach corner cases, which are then run in the more scalable simulation environment.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Modern SoCs employ sophisticated power-management techniques to conserve energy, such as power gating and multiple voltage domains.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Verifying the correct functionality of these low-power features is a major task that involves ensuring logic states are correctly isolated, retained, and restored during power-down and power-up sequences.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] This is typically managed by specifying the power intent in a standardized format, such as the Unified Power Format (UPF), which guides the verification tools.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Complex SoCs often contain multiple clock domains that operate asynchronously to one another.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Passing data reliably between these domains is a common source of subtle hardware bugs.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] CDC verification focuses on identifying and ensuring the correctness of synchronizer circuits used at these asynchronous boundaries to prevent issues like metastability and data corruption.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Specialized static analysis and formal verification tools are essential for comprehensive CDC verification.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] Machine learning (ML) is being applied to various aspects of functional verification to improve efficiency and effectiveness.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] ML models can analyze large datasets from the verification process to identify patterns and make predictions.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] As electronic systems become more integrated into critical applications (e.g., AI, automotive), ensuring hardware security has become a key part of verification.
[src:uvm-verification/functional-verification] The process is now being adapted to detect security vulnerabilities in addition to functional bugs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In programming and software development, **fuzzing** or **fuzz testing** is an automated software testing technique that involves providing invalid, unexpected, or random data as inputs to a computer program.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The program is then monitored for exceptions such as crashes, failing built-in code assertions, or potential memory leaks.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Typically, fuzzers are used to test programs that take structured inputs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] This structure is specified, such as in a file format or protocol and distinguishes valid from invalid input.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] An effective fuzzer generates semi-valid inputs that are "valid enough" in that they are not directly rejected by the parser, but do create unexpected behaviors deeper in the program and are "invalid enough" to expose corner cases that have not been properly dealt with.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For the purpose of security, input that crosses a trust boundary is often the most useful.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For example, it is more important to fuzz code that handles a file uploaded by any user than it is to fuzz the code that parses a configuration file that is accessible only to a privileged user.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The term "fuzz" originates from a 1988 class project in the graduate Advanced Operating Systems class (CS736), taught by Prof.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Barton Miller at the University of Wisconsin, whose results were subsequently published in 1990.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] To fuzz test a UNIX utility meant to automatically generate random input and command-line parameters for the utility.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The project was designed to test the reliability of UNIX command line programs by executing a large number of random inputs in quick succession until they crashed.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Miller's team was able to crash 25 to 33 percent of the utilities that they tested.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] They then debugged each of the crashes to determine the cause and categorized each detected failure.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] To allow other researchers to conduct similar experiments with other software, the source code of the tools, the test procedures, and the raw result data were made publicly available.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] This early fuzzing would now be called black box, generational, unstructured (dumb or "classic") fuzzing.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Barton Miller, "In the process of writing the project description, I needed to give this kind of testing a name.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] I wanted a name that would evoke the feeling of random, unstructured data.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A key contribution of this early work was simple (almost simplistic) oracle.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A program failed its test if it crashed or hung under the random input and was considered to have passed otherwise.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] While test oracles can be challenging to construct, the oracle for this early fuzz testing was simple and universal to apply.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In April 2012, Google announced ClusterFuzz, a cloud-based fuzzing infrastructure for security-critical components of the Chromium web browser.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Security researchers can upload their own fuzzers and collect bug bounties if ClusterFuzz finds a crash with the uploaded fuzzer.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In September 2014, Shellshock was disclosed as a family of security bugs in the widely used UNIX Bash shell; most vulnerabilities of Shellshock were found using the fuzzer AFL.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] (Many Internet-facing services, such as some web server deployments, use Bash to process certain requests, allowing an attacker to cause vulnerable versions of Bash to execute arbitrary commands.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In April 2015, Hanno Böck showed how the fuzzer AFL could have found the 2014 Heartbleed vulnerability.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] (The Heartbleed vulnerability was disclosed in April 2014.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] It is a serious vulnerability that allows adversaries to decipher otherwise encrypted communication.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The vulnerability was accidentally introduced into OpenSSL which implements TLS and is used by the majority of the servers on the internet.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In August 2016, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) held the finals of the first Cyber Grand Challenge, a fully automated capture-the-flag competition that lasted 11 hours.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The objective was to develop automatic defense systems that can discover, exploit, and correct software flaws in real-time.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Fuzzing was used as an effective offense strategy to discover flaws in the software of the opponents.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] It showed tremendous potential in the automation of vulnerability detection.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The winner was a system called "Mayhem" developed by the team ForAllSecure led by David Brumley.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In September 2016, Microsoft announced Project Springfield, a cloud-based fuzz testing service for finding security critical bugs in software.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In December 2016, Google announced OSS-Fuzz which allows for continuous fuzzing of several security-critical open-source projects.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] At Black Hat 2018, Christopher Domas demonstrated the use of fuzzing to expose the existence of a hidden RISC core in a processor.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] This core was able to bypass existing security checks to execute Ring 0 commands from Ring 3.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In September 2020, Microsoft released OneFuzz, a self-hosted fuzzing-as-a-service platform that automates the detection of software bugs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] It was archived three years later on November 1, 2023.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Testing programs with random inputs dates back to the 1950s when data was still stored on punched cards.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Programmers would use punched cards that were pulled from the trash or card decks of random numbers as input to computer programs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] If an execution revealed undesired behavior, a bug had been detected.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The execution of random inputs is also called random testing, monkey testing or Monte Carlo debugging (in analogy to Monte Carlo methods).
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In 1981, Duran and Ntafos formally investigated the effectiveness of testing a program with random inputs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] While random testing had been widely perceived to be the worst means of testing a program, the authors could show that it is a cost-effective alternative to more systematic testing techniques.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In 1983, Steve Capps at Apple developed "The Monkey", a tool that would generate random inputs for classic Mac OS applications, such as MacPaint.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The figurative "monkey" refers to the infinite monkey theorem which states that a monkey hitting keys at random on a typewriter keyboard for an infinite amount of time will eventually type out the entire works of Shakespeare.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In the case of testing, the monkey would write the particular sequence of inputs that would trigger a crash.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In 1991, the crashme tool was released, which was intended to test the robustness of Unix and Unix-like operating systems by randomly executing systems calls with randomly chosen parameters.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A fuzzer can be dumb (unstructured) or smart (structured) depending on whether it is aware of input structure.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A fuzzer can be white-, grey-, or black-box, depending on whether it is aware of program structure.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A mutation-based fuzzer leverages an existing corpus of seed inputs during fuzzing.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] It generates inputs by modifying (or rather mutating) the provided seeds.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For example, when fuzzing the image library libpng, the user would provide a set of valid PNG image files as seeds while a mutation-based fuzzer would modify these seeds to produce semi-valid variants of each seed.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The corpus of seed files may contain thousands of potentially similar inputs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Automated seed selection (or test suite reduction) allows users to pick the best seeds in order to maximize the total number of bugs found during a fuzz campaign.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A generation-based fuzzer generates inputs from scratch.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, a smart generation-based fuzzer takes the input model that was provided by the user to generate new inputs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Unlike mutation-based fuzzers, a generation-based fuzzer does not depend on the existence or quality of a corpus of seed inputs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Some fuzzers have the capability to do both, to generate inputs from scratch and to generate inputs by mutation of existing seeds.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Typically, fuzzers are used to generate inputs for programs that take structured inputs, such as a file, a sequence of keyboard or mouse events, or a sequence of messages.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] This structure distinguishes valid input that is accepted and processed by the program from invalid input that is quickly rejected by the program.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] What constitutes a valid input may be explicitly specified in an input model.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Examples of input models are formal grammars, file formats, GUI-models, and network protocols.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Even items not normally considered as input can be fuzzed, such as the contents of databases, shared memory, environment variables or the precise interleaving of threads.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] An effective fuzzer generates semi-valid inputs that are "valid enough" so that they are not directly rejected from the parser and "invalid enough" so that they might stress corner cases and exercise interesting program behaviours.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A smart (model-based, grammar-based, or protocol-based) fuzzer leverages the input model to generate a greater proportion of valid inputs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, if the input can be modelled as an abstract syntax tree, then a smart mutation-based fuzzer would employ random transformations to move complete subtrees from one node to another.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] If the input can be modelled by a formal grammar, a smart generation-based fuzzer would instantiate the production rules to generate inputs that are valid with respect to the grammar.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] However, generally the input model must be explicitly provided, which is difficult to do when the model is proprietary, unknown, or very complex.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] If a large corpus of valid and invalid inputs is available, a grammar induction technique, such as Angluin's L* algorithm, would be able to generate an input model.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A dumb fuzzer does not require the input model and can thus be employed to fuzz a wider variety of programs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, AFL is a dumb mutation-based fuzzer that modifies a seed file by flipping random bits, by substituting random bytes with "interesting" values, and by moving or deleting blocks of data.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] However, a dumb fuzzer might generate a lower proportion of valid inputs and stress the parser code rather than the main components of a program.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The disadvantage of dumb fuzzers can be illustrated by means of the construction of a valid checksum for a cyclic redundancy check (CRC).
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A CRC is an error-detecting code that ensures that the integrity of the data contained in the input file is preserved during transmission.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A checksum is computed over the input data and recorded in the file.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] When the program processes the received file and the recorded checksum does not match the re-computed checksum, then the file is rejected as invalid.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Now, a fuzzer that is unaware of the CRC is unlikely to generate the correct checksum.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] However, there are attempts to identify and re-compute a potential checksum in the mutated input, once a dumb mutation-based fuzzer has modified the protected data.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Typically, a fuzzer is considered more effective if it achieves a higher degree of code coverage.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The rationale is, if a fuzzer does not exercise certain structural elements in the program, then it is also not able to reveal bugs that are hiding in these elements.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Some program elements are considered more critical than others.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, a division operator might cause a division by zero error, or a system call may crash the program.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A black-box fuzzer treats the program as a black box and is unaware of internal program structure.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, a random testing tool that generates inputs at random is considered a blackbox fuzzer.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Hence, a blackbox fuzzer can execute several hundred inputs per second, can be easily parallelized, and can scale to programs of arbitrary size.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] However, blackbox fuzzers may only scratch the surface and expose "shallow" bugs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Hence, there are attempts to develop blackbox fuzzers that can incrementally learn about the internal structure (and behavior) of a program during fuzzing by observing the program's output given an input.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, LearnLib employs active learning to generate an automaton that represents the behavior of a web application.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A white-box fuzzer leverages program analysis to systematically increase code coverage or to reach certain critical program locations.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, SAGE leverages symbolic execution to systematically explore different paths in the program (a technique known as concolic execution).
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] If the program's specification is available, a whitebox fuzzer might leverage techniques from model-based testing to generate inputs and check the program outputs against the program specification.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A whitebox fuzzer can be very effective at exposing bugs that hide deep in the program.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] However, the time used for analysis (of the program or its specification) can become prohibitive.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] If the whitebox fuzzer takes relatively too long to generate an input, a blackbox fuzzer will be more efficient.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Hence, there are attempts to combine the efficiency of blackbox fuzzers and the effectiveness of whitebox fuzzers.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A gray-box fuzzer leverages instrumentation rather than program analysis to glean information about the program.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, AFL and libFuzzer utilize lightweight instrumentation to trace basic block transitions exercised by an input.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] This leads to a reasonable performance overhead but informs the fuzzer about the increase in code coverage during fuzzing, which makes gray-box fuzzers extremely efficient vulnerability detection tools.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Fuzzing is used mostly as an automated technique to expose vulnerabilities in security-critical programs that might be exploited with malicious intent.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] More generally, fuzzing is used to demonstrate the presence of bugs rather than their absence.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Running a fuzzing campaign for several weeks without finding a bug does not prove the program correct.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] After all, the program may still fail for an input that has not been executed, yet; executing a program for all inputs is prohibitively expensive.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] If the objective is to prove a program correct for all inputs, a formal specification must exist and techniques from formal methods must be used.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In order to expose bugs, a fuzzer must be able to distinguish expected (normal) from unexpected (buggy) program behavior.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] However, a machine cannot always distinguish a bug from a feature.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] In automated software testing, this is also called the test oracle problem.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Typically, a fuzzer distinguishes between crashing and non-crashing inputs in the absence of specifications and to use a simple and objective measure.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Crashes can be easily identified and might indicate potential vulnerabilities (e.g., denial of service or arbitrary code execution).
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] However, the absence of a crash does not indicate the absence of a vulnerability.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, a program written in C may or may not crash when an input causes a buffer overflow.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Rather the program's behavior is undefined.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] To make a fuzzer more sensitive to failures other than crashes, sanitizers can be used to inject assertions that crash the program when a failure is detected.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Fuzzing can also be used to detect "differential" bugs if a reference implementation is available.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For automated regression testing, the generated inputs are executed on two versions of the same program.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For automated differential testing, the generated inputs are executed on two implementations of the same program (e.g., lighttpd and httpd are both implementations of a web server).
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] If the two variants produce different output for the same input, then one may be buggy and should be examined more closely.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Static program analysis analyzes a program without actually executing it.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] This might lead to false positives where the tool reports problems with the program that do not actually exist.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Fuzzing in combination with dynamic program analysis can be used to try to generate an input that actually witnesses the reported problem.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Modern web browsers undergo extensive fuzzing.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The Chromium code of Google Chrome is continuously fuzzed by the Chrome Security Team with 15,000 cores.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For Microsoft Edge [Legacy] and Internet Explorer, Microsoft performed fuzzed testing with 670 machine-years during product development, generating more than 400 billion DOM manipulations from 1 billion HTML files.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A fuzzer produces a large number of inputs in a relatively short time.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, in 2016 the Google OSS-fuzz project produced around 4 trillion inputs a week.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Hence, many fuzzers provide a toolchain that automates otherwise manual and tedious tasks which follow the automated generation of failure-inducing inputs.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Automated bug triage is used to group a large number of failure-inducing inputs by root cause and to prioritize each individual bug by severity.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] A fuzzer produces a large number of inputs, and many of the failure-inducing ones may effectively expose the same software bug.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Only some of these bugs are security-critical and should be patched with higher priority.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance the CERT Coordination Center provides the Linux triage tools which group crashing inputs by the produced stack trace and lists each group according to their probability to be exploitable.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Previously unreported, triaged bugs might be automatically reported to a bug tracking system.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, OSS-Fuzz runs large-scale, long-running fuzzing campaigns for several security-critical software projects where each previously unreported, distinct bug is reported directly to a bug tracker.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The OSS-Fuzz bug tracker automatically informs the maintainer of the vulnerable software and checks in regular intervals whether the bug has been fixed in the most recent revision using the uploaded minimized failure-inducing input.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Automated input minimization (or test case reduction) is an automated debugging technique to isolate that part of the failure-inducing input that is actually inducing the failure.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] If the failure-inducing input is large and mostly malformed, it might be difficult for a developer to understand what exactly is causing the bug.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] Given the failure-inducing input, an automated minimization tool would remove as many input bytes as possible while still reproducing the original bug.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] For instance, Delta Debugging is an automated input minimization technique that employs an extended binary search algorithm to find such a minimal input.
[src:uvm-verification/fuzzing] The following is a list of fuzzers described as "popular", "widely used", or similar in the academic literature.
[src:uvm-verification/hardware-verification-language] A **hardware verification language**, or **HVL**, is a programming language used to verify the designs of electronic circuits written in a hardware description language.
[src:uvm-verification/hardware-verification-language] HVLs typically include features of a high-level programming language like C++ or Java as well as features for easy bit-level manipulation similar to those found in HDLs.
[src:uvm-verification/hardware-verification-language] Many HVLs will provide constrained random stimulus generation, and functional coverage constructs to assist with complex hardware verification.
[src:uvm-verification/hardware-verification-language] SystemVerilog, OpenVera, e, and SystemC are the most commonly used HVLs.
[src:uvm-verification/hardware-verification-language] SystemVerilog attempts to combine HDL and HVL constructs into a single standard.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] Random testing for hardware was first examined by Melvin Breuer in 1971 and initial effort to evaluate its effectiveness was done by Pratima and Vishwani Agrawal in 1975.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] In software, Duran and Ntafos had examined random testing in 1984.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] The use of hypothesis testing as a theoretical basis for random testing was described by Howden in *Functional Testing and Analysis*.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] The book also contained the development of a simple formula for estimating the number of tests *n* that are needed to have confidence at least 1-1/*n* in a failure rate of no larger than 1/n.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] The formula is the lower bound *n*log*n*, which indicates the large number of failure-free tests needed to have even modest confidence in a modest failure rate bound.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] Now the random tests for this function could be {123, 36, -35, 48, 0}.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] If there is no reference implementation to check the result, the bug still could go unnoticed.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] The reference implementation is sometimes available, e.g. when implementing a simple algorithm in a much more complex way for better performance.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] Such approaches then maintain a pool of randomly generated objects and use a probability for either reusing a generated object or creating a new one.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] According to the seminal paper on random testing by D.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] A test oracle is an instrument for verifying whether the outcomes match the program specification or not.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] An operation profile is knowledge about usage patterns of the program and thus which parts are more important.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] For programming languages and platforms which have contracts (e.g.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] Eiffel. .NET or various extensions of Java like JML, CoFoJa...) contracts act as natural oracles and the approach has been applied successfully.
[src:uvm-verification/random-testing] In particular, random testing finds more bugs than manual inspections or user reports (albeit different ones).
[src:uvm-verification/test-bench] A **test bench** or **testing workbench** is an environment used to verify the correctness or soundness of a design or model.
[src:uvm-verification/test-bench] The term has its roots in the testing of electronic devices, where an engineer would sit at a lab bench with tools for measurement and manipulation, such as oscilloscopes, multimeters, soldering irons, wire cutters, and so on, and manually verify the correctness of the device under test (DUT).
[src:uvm-verification/test-bench] In the context of software or firmware or hardware engineering, a test bench is an environment in which the product under development is tested with the aid of software and hardware tools.
[src:uvm-verification/test-bench] The software may need to be modified slightly in some cases to work with the test bench but careful coding can ensure that the changes can be undone easily and without introducing bugs.
[src:uvm-verification/test-bench] The term "test bench" is used in digital design with a hardware description language to describe the test code, which instantiates the DUT and runs the test.
[src:uvm-verification/test-bench] An additional meaning for "test bench" is an isolated, controlled environment, very similar to the production environment but neither hidden nor visible to the general public, customers etc.
[src:uvm-verification/test-bench] Therefore making changes is safe, because final users are not involved.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] The **Universal Verification Methodology** (**UVM**) is a standardized methodology for verifying integrated circuit designs.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] UVM is derived mainly from OVM (Open Verification Methodology) which was, to a large part, based on the eRM (e Reuse Methodology) for the e verification language developed by Verisity Design in 2001.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] On February 21, 2011, Accellera approved the 1.0 version of UVM.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] UVM 1.0 includes a Reference Guide, a Reference Implementation in the form of a SystemVerilog base class library, and a User Guide.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] A factory is a commonly used concept in object-oriented programming.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] It is an object that is used for instantiating other objects.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] There are two ways to register an object with the UVM factory.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] In the declaration of class A, one can invoke the `uvm_object_utils(A) or `uvm_component_utils(A) registration macros.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] Otherwise, the `uvm_object_registry(A,B) or `uvm_component_registry(A,B) macros can be used to map a string B to a class type A.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] The UVM factory provides a variety of create methods that allow the user to instantiate an object with a particular instance name and of a registered type.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] In this stage the DUT (Design Under Test) and the test bench environment should be set to the desired initial conditions.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] A scoreboard can be implemented in various ways.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] Generally speaking, a scoreboard takes the inputs to and outputs from the DUT, determines what the input-output relationship should be, and judges whether the DUT adheres to the specification.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] This input-output relationship is often specified by a model, called a predictor.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] The predictor may be implemented in a higher-level programming language, like SystemC.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] UVM scoreboard classes are implemented as subclasses of the uvm_scoreboard class, which itself is a subclass of uvm_component. uvm_scoreboard is a blank slate for implementing a scoreboard.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] It only contains one class method, namely the "new" constructor method.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] The rest of the implementation is user-defined.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] In modern VLSI, a DUT may have multiple interfaces.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] Each of these interfaces may have different UVM objects associated with them.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] For instance, if the DUT is the full-chip, there may be separate interfaces for PCI, Ethernet, and other communication standards.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] The scoreboard and monitor for a PCI interface will be different from the ones for the Ethernet interface.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] The various UVM objects can be organized as members of a wrapper class known as an agent.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] Passive agents will only analyze port values of the interface and should contain a monitor member.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] Active agents will drive ports and should contain a driver member, perhaps in addition to a monitor member.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] UVM agent classes are implemented as subclasses of the uvm_agent class, which itself is a subclass of uvm_component.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] Much like uvm_scoreboard, uvm_agent is lightweight in terms of class methods.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] Its only class methods are the "new" constructor and the "get_is_active" method.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] If the agent is being used to drive ports, get_is_active returns UVM_ACTIVE.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] Otherwise, get_is_active returns UVM_PASSIVE.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] Sequence items for a test are described abstractly.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] For example, if the DUT is a register file, it may have ports for a read address and a write address.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] The sequence item object may have member variables for the read address and the write address.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] However, these values need to eventually become bits at the input pins to the DUT.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] There may even be an exotic encoding used when providing the stimulus to the DUT that should be abstracted from the rest of the agent.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] The driver's responsibility is to take these sequence items and provide the proper stimulus to the DUT's ports.
[src:uvm-verification/universal-verification-methodology] UVM driver classes are implemented as subclasses of the uvm_driver class, which itself is a subclass of uvm_component.
